India's New Hope
Cambridge, US—India’s latest election could be the most important positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which had ruled India almost continuously since independence from Britain in 1947.
They might feel pleased with this decision.
The party leader and former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi’s widow Sonia Gandhi has been behind the scenes since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh was little more than a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's annual growth rate dropping below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised in his campaign to bring rapid job and income growth across all of India, as he did when he was Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with economic activity expanding and attracting both domestic and foreign business investment.
A key feature of the latest election was the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) winning an absolute majority in Parliament, which can be considered a remarkable achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will help Modi with his economic plans.
The new Finance Minister Arun Jaitley, who is politically experienced, served as a minister in the previous BJP government.
Jaitley is also known as a strategic thinker who favors business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India ( central bank). Rajan, an outstanding economist, showed a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate during his tenure as governor and attempted to reform some inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to implement and bear fruit.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should look at progress in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
While India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small fraction of people can access the opportunities they offer because primary and secondary education in India is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults can read and write at a primary school level.
Teachers themselves have low levels of education and lack motivation, with many teachers not even showing up at their assigned schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private airlines and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal consolidation.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that could be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that must be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
The government-owned manufacturing and other industrial enterprises in India operate inefficiently, often resulting in the depletion of national savings.
Selling these enterprises would directly help accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Energy subsidies lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, India’s cash transfer system is more efficient due to the implementation of a notable fingerprint-based new program.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government buys, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is significant stockpiling of goods in warehouses while production incentives are misaligned.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and land zoning.
Just visit Mumbai or any other Indian metropolis, and you'll see how land use in towns is suboptimal due to zoning restrictions, which hinder development.
Inadequate property rights, particularly those related to agricultural land, have prevented industrialization in rural areas.
Relax foreign investment constraints.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reforms.
India's complex national and state-level sales tax regime distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a nationwide value-added tax and adopting a federal system has been ongoing for a long time and should now enter the implementation phase.
Corruption.
Major cases of corruption at higher levels undermine economic confidence and hinder official decision-making.
India is also plagued by petty corruption on a smaller scale, with bribery becoming a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should crack down on high-level corruption and limit petty corruption through new cash transfer programs.
Driven by stronger growth and expectations of rising profits, India’s stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can deliver on their election promises.
